# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: augarchaeota
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:augarchaeota/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:augarchaeota/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:augarchaeota/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:augarchaeota/aerophobota] The classification is based on genomic and metagenomic data without cultured isolates, and the name is not yet validly published under formal bacterial nomenclature.
[src:augarchaeota/aerophobota] Aerophobetes are abundant in hydrate-containing, silty sediment layers beneath the ocean floor and thrive in anoxic (oxygen-free) conditions.
[src:augarchaeota/aerophobota] Genetic analyses suggest they ferment organic matter, producing hydrogen and acetate, which can then be used by syntrophic methanogenic archaea to generate methane.
[src:augarchaeota/aerophobota] These metabolic interactions indicate Aerophobota's likely contribution to methane formation and carbon cycling in deep-sea ecosystems.
[src:augarchaeota/aerophobota] Research into Aerophobota and its functional roles is of interest because methane is a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:augarchaeota/aerophobota] Understanding these microbes could inform strategies for mitigating methane emissions from seafloor hydrates.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Some are only 10–20 μm in diameter, while others are among the largest protozoa.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The well-known species *Amoeba proteus,* which may reach 800 μm in length, is often studied in schools and laboratories as a representative cell or model organism, partly because of its convenient size.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Multinucleate amoebae like *Chaos* and *Pelomyxa* may be several millimetres in length, and some multicellular amoebozoa, such as the "dog vomit" slime mold *Fuligo septica*, can cover an area of several square meters.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Amoebozoa is a large and diverse group, but certain features are common to many of its members.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The amoebozoan cell is typically divided into a granular central mass, called endoplasm, and a clear outer layer, called ectoplasm.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] During locomotion, the endoplasm flows forwards and the ectoplasm runs backwards along the outside of the cell.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] In motion, many amoebozoans have a clearly defined anterior and posterior and may assume a "monopodial" form, with the entire cell functioning as a single pseudopod.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Large pseudopods may produce numerous clear projections called subpseudopodia (or determinate pseudopodia), which are extended to a certain length and then retracted, either for the purpose of locomotion or food intake.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] A cell may also form multiple indeterminate pseudopodia, through which the entire contents of the cell flow in the direction of locomotion.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] These are more or less tubular and are mostly filled with granular endoplasm.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The cell mass flows into a leading pseudopod, and the others ultimately retract, unless the organism changes direction.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] While most amoebozoans are "naked," like the familiar *Amoeba* and *Chaos*, or covered with a loose coat of minute scales, like *Cochliopodium* and *Korotnevella*, members of the order Arcellinida form rigid shells, or tests, equipped with a single aperture through which the pseudopods emerge.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] In all amoebozoa, the primary mode of nutrition is phagocytosis, in which the cell surrounds potential food particles with its pseudopods, sealing them into vacuoles within which they may be digested and absorbed.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Some amoebozoans have a posterior bulb called a uroid, which may serve to accumulate waste, periodically detaching from the rest of the cell.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] When food is scarce, most species can form cysts, which may be carried aerially and introduce them to new environments.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] In slime moulds, these structures are called spores, and form on stalked structures called fruiting bodies or sporangia.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Mixotrophic species living in a symbiotic relationship with microalgae of the genus Chlorella, which lives inside the cytoplasm of their host, have been found in Arcellinida and *Mayorella*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The majority of Amoebozoa lack flagella and more generally do not form microtubule-supported structures except during mitosis.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] However, flagella do occur among the Archamoebae, and many slime moulds produce biflagellate gametes .
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The flagellum is generally anchored by a cone of microtubules, suggesting a close relationship to the opisthokonts.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The mitochondria in amoebozoan cells characteristically have branching tubular cristae.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] However, among the Archamoebae, which are adapted to anoxic or microaerophilic habitats, mitochondria have been lost.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Strong similarities between Amoebozoa and Opisthokonts lead to the hypothesis that they form a distinct clade.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] In their Revised Classification of Eukaryotes (2012), Adl et al. proposed Amorphea as a more suitable name for a clade of approximately the same composition, a sister group to the Diaphoretickes.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] More recent work places the members of Amorphea together with the malawimonids and collodictyonids in a proposed clade called Opimoda, which comprises one of two major lineages diverging at the root of the eukaryote tree of life, the other being Diphoda.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Traditionally all amoebozoa with lobose pseudopods were grouped together in the class Lobosea, placed with other amoeboids in the phylum Sarcodina or Rhizopoda, but these were considered to be unnatural groups.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Structural and genetic studies identified the percolozoans and several archamoebae as independent groups.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] In phylogenies based on rRNA their representatives were separate from other amoebae, and appeared to diverge near the base of eukaryotic evolution, as did most slime molds.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] However, revised trees by Cavalier-Smith and Chao in 1996 suggested that the remaining lobosans do form a monophyletic group, to which the Archamoebae and Mycetozoa were closely related, although the percolozoans were not.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Subsequently, they emended the phylum Amoebozoa to include both the subphylum Lobosa and a new subphylum Conosa, comprising the Archamoebae and the Mycetozoa.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Recent molecular genetic data appear to support this primary division of the Amoebozoa into Lobosa and Conosa.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The former, as defined by Cavalier-Smith and his collaborators, consists largely of the classic Lobosea: non-flagellated amoebae with blunt, lobose pseudopods (*Amoeba*, *Acanthamoeba, Arcella, Difflugia etc.*).
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The latter is made up of both amoeboid and flagellated cells, characteristically with more pointed or slightly branching subpseudopodia (Archamoebae and the Mycetozoan slime molds).
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] From older studies by Cavalier-Smith, Chao & Lewis 2016 and Silar 2016.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Also recent phylogeny indicates the Lobosa are paraphyletic: Conosa is sister of the Cutosea.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Vase-shaped microfossils (VSMs) discovered around the world show that amoebozoans have existed since the Neoproterozoic Era.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The fossil species *Melanocyrillium hexodiadema*, *Palaeoarcella athanata*, and *Hemisphaeriella ornata* come from rocks 750 million years old.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] All three VSMs share a hemispherical shape, invaginated aperture, and regular indentations, that strongly resemble modern arcellinids, which are shell-bearing amoebozoans belonging to the class Tubulinea.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] *P. athanata* in particular looks the same as the extant genus *Arcella*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The recently available *Acanthamoeba* genome sequence revealed several orthologs of genes employed in meiosis of sexual eukaryotes.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] This finding suggests that *Acanthamoeba* is capable of some form of meiosis and may be able to undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] In sexually reproducing eukaryotes, homologous recombination (HR) ordinarily occurs during meiosis.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The meiosis-specific recombinase, Dmc1, is required for efficient meiotic HR, and Dmc1 is expressed in *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The purified Dmc1 from *E. histolytica* forms presynaptic filaments and catalyzes ATP-dependent homologous DNA pairing and DNA strand exchange over at least several thousand base pairs.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The DNA pairing and strand exchange reactions are enhanced by the eukaryotic meiosis-specific recombination accessory factor (heterodimer) Hop2-Mnd1.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] These processes are central to meiotic recombination, suggesting that *E. histolytica* undergoes meiosis.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Studies of *Entamoeba invadens* found that, during the conversion from the tetraploid uninucleate trophozoite to the tetranucleate cyst, homologous recombination is enhanced.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Expression of genes with functions related to the major steps of meiotic recombination also increased during encystations.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] These findings in *E. invadens*, combined with evidence from studies of *E. histolytica* indicate the presence of meiosis in the *Entamoeba*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] A comparative genetic analysis indicated that meiotic processes are present in all major amoebozoan lineages.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Since *Amoebozoa* diverged early from the eukaryotic family tree, these results also suggest that meiosis was present early in eukaryotic evolution.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis, also known as amebiasis or entamoebiasis, is an infection caused by any of the amoebozoans of the *Entamoeba* group.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Symptoms are most common upon infection by *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis can present with no, mild, or severe symptoms.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Symptoms may include abdominal pain, mild diarrhoea, bloody diarrhea or severe colitis with tissue death and perforation.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] This last complication may cause peritonitis.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] People affected may develop anemia due to loss of blood.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Invasion of the intestinal lining causes amoebic bloody diarrhea or amoebic colitis.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] If the parasite reaches the bloodstream it can spread through the body, most frequently ending up in the liver where it causes amoebic liver abscesses.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Liver abscesses can occur without previous diarrhea.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Cysts of *Entamoeba* can survive for up to a month in soil or for up to 45 minutes under fingernails.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] It is important to differentiate between amoebiasis and bacterial colitis.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The preferred diagnostic method is through faecal examination under microscope, but requires a skilled microscopist and may not be reliable when excluding infection.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] This method however may not be able to separate between specific types.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Increased white blood cell count is present in severe cases, but not in mild ones.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The most accurate test is for antibodies in the blood, but it may remain positive following treatment.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Prevention of amoebiasis is by separating food and water from faeces and by proper sanitation measures.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] There are two treatment options depending on the location of the infection.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis in tissues is treated with either metronidazole, tinidazole, nitazoxanide, dehydroemetine or chloroquine, while luminal infection is treated with diloxanide furoate or iodoquinoline.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] For treatment to be effective against all stages of the amoeba may require a combination of medications.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Infections without symptoms do not require treatment but infected individuals can spread the parasite to others and treatment can be considered.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Treatment of other *Entamoeba* infections apart from *E. histolytica* is not needed.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis is present all over the world.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] About 480 million people are infected with what appears to be *E. histolytica* and these result in the death of between 40,000–110,000 people every year.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Most infections are now ascribed to *E. dispar*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] *E. dispar* is more common in certain areas and symptomatic cases may be fewer than previously reported.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The first case of amoebiasis was documented in 1875 and in 1891 the disease was described in detail, resulting in the terms *amoebic dysentery* and *amoebic liver abscess*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] Further evidence from the Philippines in 1913 found that upon ingesting cysts of *E. histolytica* volunteers developed the disease.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] It has been known since 1897 that at least one non-disease-causing species of *Entamoeba* existed (*Entamoeba coli*), but it was first formally recognized by the WHO in 1997 that *E. histolytica* was two species, despite this having first been proposed in 1925.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] In addition to the now-recognized *E. dispar* evidence shows there are at least two other species of *Entamoeba* that look the same in humans - *E. moshkovskii* and *Entamoeba bangladeshi*.
[src:augarchaeota/amoebozoa] The reason these species haven't been differentiated until recently is because of the reliance on appearance.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] The International Society of Protistologists, the recognised body for taxonomy of protozoa, recommended in 2012 that the term Unikont be changed to Amorphea because the name "Unikont" is based on a hypothesized synapomorphy that the ISOP authors and other scientists later rejected.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] It includes amoebozoa, opisthokonts, and apusomonads.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Thomas Cavalier-Smith proposed a new phylum: Sulcozoa, which consists of the subphyla Apusozoa (Apusomonadida and Breviatea), and Varisulca, which includes the taxa Diphyllatea, Discocelida, Mantamonadida, Planomonadida and Rigifilida.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Further work by Cavalier-Smith showed that Sulcozoa is paraphyletic.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Apusozoa also appears to be paraphyletic.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Varisulca has been redefined to include planomonads, *Mantamonas* and *Collodictyon*.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] A new taxon has been created - Glissodiscea - for the planomonads and *Mantamonas*.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Again, the validity of this revised taxonomy awaits confirmation.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Amoebozoa seems to be monophyletic with two major branches: Conosa and Lobosa.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Conosa is divided into the aerobic infraphylum Semiconosia (Mycetozoa and Variosea) and secondarily anaerobic Archamoebae.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Lobosa consists entirely of non-flagellated lobose amoebae and has been divided into two classes: Discosea, which have flattened cells, and Tubulinea, which has predominantly tube-shaped pseudopodia.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] The group includes eukaryotic cells that, for the most part, have a single emergent flagellum, or are amoebae with no flagella.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] The unikonts include opisthokonts (animals, fungi, and related forms) and Amoebozoa.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] By contrast, other well-known eukaryotic groups, which more often have two emergent flagella (although there are many exceptions), are often referred to as bikonts.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Bikonts include Archaeplastida (plants and relatives) and SAR supergroup, the Cryptista, Haptista, Telonemia and Picozoa.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] One view of the great kingdoms and their stem groups.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] The Metamonada are hard to place, being sister possibly to Discoba or to Malawimonadida or being a paraphyletic group external to all other eukaryotes.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Eukaryotes are thought to have emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] The unikonts have a triple-gene fusion that is lacking in the bikonts.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] The three genes that are fused together in the unikonts, but not bacteria or bikonts, encode enzymes for synthesis of the pyrimidine nucleotides: carbamoyl phosphate synthase, dihydroorotase and aspartate carbamoyltransferase.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] This must have involved a double fusion, a rare pair of events, supporting the shared ancestry of Opisthokonta and Amoebozoa.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] Cavalier-Smith originally proposed that unikonts ancestrally had a single flagellum and single basal body.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] This is unlikely, however, as flagellated opisthokonts, as well as some flagellated Amoebozoa, including *Breviata*, actually have two basal bodies, as in typical 'bikonts' (even though only one is flagellated in most unikonts).
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] This paired arrangement can also be seen in the organization of centrioles in typical animal cells.
[src:augarchaeota/amorphea] In spite of the name of the group, the common ancestor of all 'unikonts' was probably a cell with two basal bodies.
